Email: krivdin55@gmail.com Theoretical calculation of 13C NMR chemical shifts provides a powerful tool in structural elucidation of organic molecules, natural compounds, and biochemical species. Theoretical grounds of the calculation of NMR parameters is well covered in a handbook of molecular electromagnetism [1] and in a number of more specialized reviews on NMR computational and theoretical aspects [2–8] involving calculation of 13C NMR chemical shifts [9–11] being the subject of the present communication. In this regard, a representative family of natural antimalarial alkaloids presents a rig- orous test and a challenging task for the calculation of 13C NMR chemical shifts of very large molecules. In this paper, we performed such calcula- tions at the DFT level using the most suitable for this purpose PBE0 functional in combination with highly economical triple zeta basis set 3z-S, which was introduced in one of our most recent publication [12]. Herewith, we test our new basis set on a series of 16 alkaloids 1–16 having in common strong antimalarial activity. parasitic species to the mainstay drugs like chloroquine. The later involve quinine (1), neoquassin ether (2), korundamine A (3), cycleanine (4), 100-hydroxyusambarensine (5), sarachine (6), matopensine (7), acantholactam (8), vertine (9), lobatin B (10), domesticulide B (11), bielschowskysin (12), oxojatrophadiene (13), jasplakinolide Q (14), ellagic acid (15), and trioxacarcin D (16) shown in Scheme 1. Identified conformers of the lowest energy were subjected to further geometry reoptimization at the M06-2X/cc-pVQZ level with the GAUSSIAN 09 [37] code. For nitro- gen and oxygen atoms, the extended aug-cc-pVQZ basis set was used to take into account the effects of the diffused lone pairs. All calculated structures were identified as minima on their potential energy surfaces proved by the absence of imaginary frequencies. The solvent effects were accounted for in the performed calculations within the Integral Equation Formalism Polarizable Continuum Model (IEF-PCM) [38, 39]. Cartesian coordinates of the optimized structures of 1–16 are given in the Supporting Information. for a liquid phase by implying the GAUSSIAN 09 code. In these calculations, we used the functional of Perdew, Burke, and Ernzerhof [40, 41] with a predetermined amount of the exact exchange known as PBE0 [42]. This functional was used in combination with the LDBS scheme [43, 44] implying a newly developed NMR-oriented split-valence 3z-S basis set of triple-zeta quality [12] for carbons oriented on the calculation of 13C NMR chemical

shifts. For the rest of nuclei (hydrogen, nitrogen, oxygen) the segmented contracted basis set of Jensen pcseg-2 [45] was applied. To test the perfor- mance of 3z-S, we have carried out similar calculations of 13C NMR chemical shifts in the series of 1–16 with the same functional (PBE0) using double- zeta quality basis set 6-31G(d,p) [46] and triple-zeta quality basis sets 6-311+G(2d,p) [47], pcSseg-2 [48], and cc-pVTZ [49] on carbons. Calculated 13C isotropic magnetic shielding constants were converted into 13C NMR chemical shifts as recommended by the International Union of Pure and Applied Chemistry [50]. To take into account the systematic error of calculated 13C NMR chemical shifts, we have established correlations between their calculated and experimental values. These correlations were used further on to find out the linear correlation equations of the y = ax + b type. The slope a and intercept b were then used for recalculating theoretical chemical shifts into experimental δ-scale using the equation δrecalc = (δcalc − b)/a. All calculations of 13C NMR isotropic magnetic shielding constants (the latter being converted to chemical shifts) were carried out at the DFT level | C O M P U T A T I O N A L D E T A I L S As it has been already mentioned in the Introduction, we have introduced very recently a new basis set of triple zeta quality for carbon, 3z-S, pro- viding very good accuracy in the calculation of 13C NMR chemical shifts, comparable to that of the NMR-oriented Jensen's triple zeta pcS-2 basis set, the latter being of one and a half times larger in size. Herewith, this new highly economical basis set 3z-S was tested on a series of 16 very large diverse plant and marine antimalarial natural products 1–16 shown in Figure 1. The latter presents their optimized 3D structures together with calculated 13C NMR chemical shifts of their asymmetric centers, as compared to experiment.

We see that in general a good conformity is observed between calculated and experimental data with several sporadic deviations of up to 10 ppm. The most demonstrative example of this inconsistency is observed in trioxacarcin D (16) for the α-carbon of the “upper” tetrahydropyran cycle (calculated 88.2 ppm vs. experimental 98.1 ppm) which might be ascribed to the underestimation of electron correlation at this level. Sur- prisingly, this is not observed for the “lower” tetrahydropyran cycle (calculated 96.6 ppm vs. experimental 94.9 ppm). It seems that strong stereo- electronic effects of two oxygen atoms were not accounted in full at the used level of theory. Presented in Figure 2 are the statistical parameters of the correlation between calculated and experimental 13C NMR chemical shifts for the double zeta 6-31G(d,p) and four triple zeta basis sets—highly economical Rusakov's 3z-S against Pople's 6-311+G(2d,p) and much larger Jensen's pcSseg-2 and Dunning's cc-pVTZ. It is seen that corrected mean absolute error (CMAE) for the calculated values of 13C NMR chemical shifts in the whole series of 1–16 are practically the same (2.12–2.20 ppm). At that, a computational cost was found to be 62% for the double zeta 6-31G(d,p) as compared to more expensive triple zeta basis sets (100% for 3z-S, 130% for 6-311+G(2d,p), 150% for cc-pVTZ, and 200% for pcSseg-2). We see again that 3z-S is much more economical as compared to much larger 6-311+G(2d,p), cc-pVTZ and pcSseg-2. At that, all four triple zeta basis sets provide almost the same accuracy. At that, it should be kept in mind that statistical parameter CMAE in this case is more informative than MAE when applied to the calculation of chemical shifts of large biological objects. This is because CMAE, in contrast to MAE, takes into account all systematic errors associated with the interplay of solvent effects, ZPV corrections, and some other accuracy fac- tors. It is essential that 3z-S basis set was created especially for the calculations of chemical shifts of large biological molecules, and its effec- tiveness has been proven in comparison with other two-, three-, and four-zeta basis sets at the MP2, CCSD, and CCSD(T) levels of 3z-S is much more economical in the sense of the required number of basis set functions providing the same or even better statistical parameters, as compared to those of pcSseg-2 and cc-pVTZ. It thus follows that a new 3z-S basis set could be rec- ommended for the high-level calculations of 13C NMR chemical shifts of large natural products with a number of carbons up to several As it has already been mentioned, all basis sets under evaluation show almost the same accuracy with similar statistical indices and thus all of them could be used in the calculations of 13C NMR chemical shifts of natural products. The key difference lies in their resource intensity and, con- sequently, in the possibility of their application to the study of large natural compounds. The PBE0 functional in combination with a new highly economical triple zeta basis set 3z-S were applied for the benchmark DFT calculations of 13C NMR chemical shifts in a series of 16 plant and marine antimalarial natural products involving quinine, neoquassin ether, korundamine A, cycleanine, 100-hydroxyusambarensine, sarachine, matopensine, acantholactam, vertine, oxojatrophadiene, jasplakinolide Q, ellagic acid, and trioxacarcin D.

Indeed, the MAE and CMAE for the calculated values of 13C NMR chemical shifts in the series of the studied natural products are practically the same (MAE 4.18–4.80 ppm, CMAE 2.12–2.20 ppm), while computational cost is 100% for 3z-S, about 130% for 6-311+G(2d,p), 150% for cc-pVTZ, and as much as 200% for pcSseg-2. provided a MAE of 2 ppm in the range of about 200 ppm. In this way, a new 3z-S basis set could be recommended for the high-level calculations of 13C NMR chemical shifts of the vitally important large natural products. 30% reduction is not dramatic in the case of one single calculation, it can become cumbersome when performing a computational screening on a database of several of natural compounds.
